<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-01-18T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-01-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="471" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d471">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/141</note>
                                <head>
                                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                            State</gloss>
                                    </hi>
                                </head>
                                <opener>
                                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                                </opener>
                                <opener>
                                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 911</seg>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                                        <placeName>
                                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-01-18">January 18,
                                            1935</date>.<lb/>[Received January 30.]</dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>:</p>
                                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                                <p>In conclusion, I have the honor to report that there are
                                    indications that the British Ambassador here has been very
                                    active in endeavoring to effect a compromise between the Italian
                                    and Abyssinian points of view. In British circles here it is
                                    felt that despite the Abyssinian request for a discussion of the
                                    Walwal incident during the present session of the League of
                                    Nations Council, a settlement of the question will be reached
                                    before such discussion takes place. It appears that of the three
                                    demands made by the Italians (namely, that an apology on the
                                    part of Abyssinia be published in an official communiqué, that a
                                    cash indemnity be deposited in a bank in Eritrea to be
                                    distributed among the sufferers of the December 5th incident,
                                    and that the Abyssinians salute the Italian flag), the first two
                                    are more or less acceptable to the Abyssinians, so that at the
                                    moment the efforts of the British are being directed toward a
                                    settlement of the last question.</p>
                                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                                <closer>
                                    <signed>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Alexander Kirk</hi>
                                    </signed>
                                </closer>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>